<div class="article-body">

<p>Manganese ore prices can vary significantly between quotes — sometimes by a factor of two or more — and the reason usually comes down to a handful of variables. Understanding these helps buyers compare quotes accurately and avoid surprises at delivery.</p>

<h2>1. Mn% Content is the Biggest Driver</h2>
<p>Price scales with manganese content. Ore in the 30-32% Mn range will be priced significantly lower per tonne than 44-48% Mn ore, because the buyer is getting substantially less usable manganese per tonne shipped — and freight cost per tonne is the same regardless of grade. For buyers, it's often more useful to think in terms of price-per-unit-of-Mn rather than price-per-tonne when comparing offers across different grades.</p>

<h2>2. Incoterms — Ex-Works, FOB, CIF</h2>
<table class="incoterm-table">
  <tr><th>Incoterm</th><th>What's Included</th><th>Who Arranges Freight</th></tr>
  <tr><td>EXW (Ex-Works)</td><td>Price covers the goods at the factory gate only</td><td>Buyer arranges and pays all transport from factory to destination</td></tr>
  <tr><td>FOB (Free on Board)</td><td>Seller delivers goods loaded onto the vessel at the export port</td><td>Buyer arranges and pays sea freight and insurance from port onward</td></tr>
  <tr><td>CIF (Cost, Insurance, Freight)</td><td>Seller arranges shipping and insurance to the destination port</td><td>Seller — cost is built into the quoted price</td></tr>
</table>
<p>When comparing quotes from different suppliers, always confirm which Incoterm applies — an EXW quote will look cheaper than a CIF quote for the same ore, but the buyer's total landed cost may end up similar once freight is added.</p>

<h2>3. Domestic vs Export Pricing Structure</h2>
<p>For domestic Indian buyers, prices are typically quoted ex-works plus GST (18%) plus freight extra, with payment terms ranging from 100% advance (for new relationships/trial orders) to advance-plus-credit for established buyers. For export buyers, pricing is typically in USD on an Ex-Works, FOB, or CIF basis, with payment via TT (advance + balance against BL) or LC at sight.</p>

<h2>4. Quantity and Contract Type</h2>
<p>Trial orders (often 5-30 MT) may carry slightly different pricing than long-term contract volumes (50+ MT/month), since regular offtake allows the supplier to plan production and logistics more efficiently. Buyers placing their first order with a new supplier should expect trial-order pricing and terms (often 100% advance) before transitioning to standard contract terms.</p>

<h2>5. The Pro-Rata Grade Deduction Clause</h2>
<p>Almost all manganese ore purchase orders include a clause along these lines: if the delivered material does not meet the guaranteed Mn% (as verified by analysis at the buyer's plant), a pro-rata deduction is applied to the payment, calculated against the shortfall in Mn%. This means the "price per tonne" in a PO is effectively the price for material at the guaranteed grade — actual payment adjusts based on what's delivered. Buyers should always check this clause and understand how the deduction is calculated (usually linear, proportional to the Mn% shortfall).</p>

<h2>6. Size and Form (Lumps vs Fines)</h2>
<p>Lump ore (e.g., 25-80mm or 5-100mm) and fines (0-10mm) may be priced differently depending on the buyer's furnace requirements — some processes prefer lumps for charge stability, while others can use fines without issue. Mixed-size specifications (e.g., "5-100mm, 80% within range") are common in contracts to give some flexibility on either side.</p>

<h2>Quick Checklist Before Comparing Quotes</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Confirm the Incoterm (EXW / FOB / CIF) for every quote you compare</li>
  <li>Calculate price-per-unit-of-Mn, not just price-per-tonne, when comparing different grades</li>
  <li>Check the pro-rata deduction terms and how "final" analysis is determined</li>
  <li>Clarify whether GST/duty is included or extra</li>
  <li>Confirm payment terms match your cash flow — especially for first orders requiring advance payment</li>
</ul>

